<font color="#FF0000">MEDALS AND THE VIETNAM WAR</font><br>
<tt>Mon Jan 12 19:01:40 US/Eastern 1998
</tt><p>
Most officers that served in the Marine Corps in Vietnam were almost without a question awarded a silver star. Many of those same officers today will tell you that they didn't earn them.<br>
 <br>
I was put up for three different medals besides those I was issued. A silver star and two bronze stars, I received none and they are not mentioned nor is any reference made to them in my official military records. I had earned three rows of ribbons and didn't know it until August of last year when I received a copy of my military record.<br><br>
The wounds I received in combat, shrapnel and concussions from a grenade, for risking my life to save others, another Marine in another comapny in our same battalion did received a Medal of Honor for doing the same thing, four months later. Unfortunally, He died, for some reason I didn't and while I was treated and tagged to be medivacked those wounds are not mentioned in my records. Why? Because I decided to stay in the field and decided not be medivacked the following morning because only 12 of us remained from the original 47 of us that went in. Others in my unit were wounded two, three times on different days during that same operation and perhaps one of their wounds are listed, and they received only one purple heart. Some of their worst wounds are not listed. <br><br>
I remember a Marine, new kid, that had just gotten off the chopper and immediately he joined in an assault up a small hill. He got hit, went down got up and caught up with the assault team. He got hit again, got up and kept going, finally the third time the squad leader send him back down the hill on account we figured he was bad luck.  He never received a medal, heck we never even got to know his name.<br><br>
I didnÆt know about the medals I had been put up for, until two other Marines told me about them last year, they received them and wondered why I didn't, they remembered that I was suppose to received the silver star, I saw their certificates, same action I was on, but who knows. I know I pissed off the lieutenant often and perhaps it was one of those days where he didnÆt know if he should put me up for a medal or Court Marshall me, perhaps he was pissed off at me again when they denied it, and he never pushed for a lesser medal to be awarded. Three of us were nominated for them at the same time, and two of the others received them, heck, I was the one that set off the ambush, and killed the most gooks that night, including an NVA lieutenant, I tell you, no gratitude.<br><br>
In the Marine Corps you will find that medals and purple hearts did not come easy. You really had to do a lot and often to earn them. Our company was given a quota, and the medals were issued from the top down. They were all well earned on the fields of battle by grunts but rarely did they receive the recognition they deserved, much less medals. Heck, we were grateful to get c-rats and once every two months a new pair of socks.<br><br>
Who was it that said, &quot;Uncommon valor was a common virtue,&quot; I saw it in Nam, often by Marines that risked their lives for others. I saw things and I did things in Nam that other military units would have placed me and others among the most decorated in their units. Those are the facts, but we were never rewarded for those common combat actions. I was surprised how often and how easy other military units received medals in Nam.  But I never placed any value on medals, to many of us grunts they werenÆt important. <br><br>
I never joined the Corps for medals, never expected them, never sought them, but I know some officers in our units who did, as did some grunts and they were usually the ones that got others killed. <br>
Medals, I don't need any stinking medals, <br><br>
I like what Luke a corpsmen from the 1st century said,<br>
&quot;So you also, when you have done everything you were told to do, should say, 'We are unworthy servants; we have only done our duty'&quot; (Luke 17:10 NIV).<br><br>
We were commanded by our officers, squad leaders or others to do certain things and we did them, we did them often without being asked, because we saw the need. Sometimes we did them without telling others what we had done, those were priceless moments. We gained no merit nor did we seek out any credit. <br>
Marines I served with knew what I did and I know what they did, Today when we get together we laugh about those times and how stupid we may have looked to Charlie for risking our lives like we did. <br>
I remember once while we were pinned down (again), turning to Aggie my a-gunner and telling him, <br>
&quot;Hey, Aggie, I think we pissed them (the enemy) off again.&quot;<br>
Marines I served with gained my respect and thank God, I obtained theirs and as MTF said, <br>
ōMore importantly they will never forget me.ö <br><br>
I cried and other Marines I have spoken too have cried on the phone when I contacted them after 30 years and identified myself to them who I was, <br>
ōYou, were that crazy machine gunner that was shooting over my head, I remember you, Oh, Wow, Thank you, Thanks, THANKS, buddy, you, you were the one that saved my life, you saved our squad.ö <br>
Those are precious words to be hearing today and I have heard them a number of times from Marines in 1st, 2nd and 3rd platoons, and their officers.  I remeber what one corpsmen, told me last year, he remembered me, because he couldn't get to the wounded on account of all the incoming fire;<br>
ōCook, the reason the gooks were shooting only at you, is because none of the others could shoot without being hit, but you kept firing, the gooks must have thought you were crazy, but thatÆs what gave us the time we needed to get our men out.ö  <br>
IÆm proud of those words, of what I did, yet I never thought I did any thing heroic or worthy of a medal. They were pinned down in the rice paddies, I loved shooting the 60 and I shot at the gooks to keep their heads down, so that we could get our men out, thatÆs all.<br><br>
I didnÆt get those medals, but if I had I would give them to MTF, OD, Art, Paul or others, (heck Paul never even got recognized for his tour of service in Nam) I would give them all my medals on account I know army dudes like those nice shinny buttons and dinging silvery stuff. Marines already have a sharp uniform we donÆt have to decorate it to make it look nice. Besides IÆm already handsome without medals and for all you other gutless, cowards that are foaming at the mouth, getting ready to strike out at me for my audacity, sorry but those are the facts.  If you donÆt believe me, I donÆt care, but there are a lot of CharlieÆs that would tell you, oH!, I guess not, they arenÆt around anymore, oh Well.<br><br>
I'm Cook Barela, and those are my thoughts and what I did during the war, but no medals. I guess maybe I can go over to the Army/Navy surplus store and buy a few as well as camoflage shirts and trousers and wear them like the protestors did during the 60's. <br>
Naw, too gody! 
